visit to China to additionally humiliate the American business delegation. Chinese customs notified manufacturers and retailers that it wont be approved, blocking clearance. Despite the fact that Trump removed all previous bans on selling Nvidia hardware to China.\n\nhttps://www.ft.com/content/a30c3dd5-9383-4606-a649-fdf19c41c308\n\nIt is very bad news for Nvidia and the US.\n\nNvidia loses another China revenue stream: China was a huge market. Even compliant \"China-only\" variants (like H20 before, now gaming GPUs) are being rejected. This shrinks sales further beyond US bans, hurting revenue and inventory. Gaming/AI-adjacent chips matter for volume.\n\nThis signals Chinas self-reliance push: Beijing is accelerating domestic alternatives like Huawei and full decoupling. It shows US restrictions from 2019 are backfiring by forcing China to build its own stack faster, eroding Nvidias (and US) long-term dominance in the worlds second-biggest tech market.\n\nThis also escalates tech war. US aimed to slow Chinas AI/military progress via controls. Instead, China is closing doors on Nvidia entirely. This risks losing \"full stack\" influence, boosts Chinese chipmakers, and could fragment global semiconductor market permanently. ", "author": "OrangeManNotBad", "created": 1779274265399, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "covfefe77", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "China has banned imports and sales of Nvidias GeForce RTX 5090 gaming GPU. ", "last_comment_created": 1779281606611, "content": "<p>This happened during Nvidia CEO Jensen Huangs visit to China to additionally humiliate the American business delegation. Chinese customs notified manufacturers and retailers that it wont be approved, blocking clearance. Despite the fact that Trump removed all previous bans on selling Nvidia hardware to China.</p>\n<p><a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.ft.com/content/a30c3dd5-9383-4606-a649-fdf19c41c308\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.ft.com/content/a30c3dd5-9383-4606-a649-fdf19c41c308</a></p>\n<p>It is very bad news for Nvidia and the US.</p>\n<p>Nvidia loses another China revenue stream: China was a huge market. Even compliant &quot;China-only&quot; variants (like H20 before, now gaming GPUs) are being rejected. This shrinks sales further beyond US bans, hurting revenue and inventory. Gaming/AI-adjacent chips matter for volume.</p>\n<p>This signals Chinas self-reliance push: Beijing is accelerating domestic alternatives like Huawei and full decoupling. It shows US restrictions from 2019 are backfiring by forcing China to build its own stack faster, eroding Nvidias (and US) long-term dominance in the worlds second-biggest tech market.</p>\n<p>This also escalates tech war. US aimed to slow Chinas AI/military progress via controls. Instead, China is closing doors on Nvidia entirely. This risks losing &quot;full stack&quot; influence, boosts Chinese chipmakers, and could fragment global semiconductor market permanently.</p>\n", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 9, "score_up": 38, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "2056770881179820507", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "link", "uuid": "1ASsUZStHe", "is_twitter": true, "is_admin": false, "score": 25, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "", "id": 8629572, "raw_content": "", "author": "rdvs34283", "created": 1779281841304, "profile_picture": "p9HQtdiLq2uP", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "Dr